Important Best Practices from Microsoft
1. Do Not Blindly Add INCLUDE Columns
Overly wide indexes:
•	increase storage
•	slow down INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE operations
•	increase maintenance cost
Only include columns frequently required by critical queries.
________________________________________
2. Avoid Duplicate Indexes
Before creating a new index:
Check:
•	existing indexes
•	overlapping definitions
•	included columns
Use:
sp_helpindex 'dbo.Orders';
Or query:
sys.indexes
sys.index_columns
________________________________________
3. Monitor Write Overhead
Every additional index affects:
•	INSERT performance
•	UPDATE performance
•	DELETE performance
•	index rebuild duration
Balance read optimization against write cost.
________________________________________
4. Validate With Actual Workload
Always test:
•	execution plans
•	logical reads
•	CPU
•	duration
•	concurrency impact

Recommended tools:
•	Query Store
•	Extended Events
•	Actual Execution Plans
•	SET STATISTICS IO, TIME ON
________________________________________
5. Watch for Lookup Threshold Changes
The optimizer may switch from:
•	Index Seek + Key Lookup
to:
•	Clustered Index Scan
when lookup cost exceeds scan cost.
This often indicates:
•	stale statistics
•	poor cardinality estimates
•	missing covering indexes
________________________________________
Key Lookup vs RID Lookup
=================================
Operator	             Table Type
=================================
Key Lookup	          Clustered table
RID Lookup	          Heap table
=================================

RID Lookups are generally more expensive because heaps lack clustering order.
Microsoft best practice recommends avoiding large heaps for transactional workloads unless specifically justified.
________________________________________
Diagnostic Script for High Lookup Queries

SELECT TOP 10
    qs.total_logical_reads,
    qs.total_worker_time,
    qs.execution_count,
    SUBSTRING(st.text,
        (qs.statement_start_offset/2)+1,
        ((CASE qs.statement_end_offset
            WHEN -1 THEN DATALENGTH(st.text)
            ELSE qs.statement_end_offset
        END - qs.statement_start_offset)/2)+1) AS query_text
FROM sys.dm_exec_query_stats qs
CROSS APPLY sys.dm_exec_sql_text(qs.sql_handle) st
ORDER BY qs.total_logical_reads DESC;

Review execution plans for these queries and check for:
•	Key Lookup
•	RID Lookup
•	excessive Nested Loop operations
________________________________________
Final Thoughts
A query showing an Index Seek is not automatically optimized.
If SQL Server must repeatedly perform Key Lookups to retrieve missing columns, the query can still become highly inefficient under scale.
The most effective fix in many cases is a carefully designed covering index using INCLUDE columns.
In modern SQL Server performance tuning, reducing unnecessary lookup operations remains one of the highest-impact optimizations for OLTP systems.

